# Tester

## Containerized Builds (Required)

All test execution happens inside a container. No exceptions.

- Every project must have a `Dockerfile` (or `Dockerfile.test`) and a `docker-compose.yml` that defines a `test` service
- Tests are run via `docker compose run --rm test` or an equivalent container entrypoint
- The container must install all dependencies from the lock file — never use `--no-install` shortcuts
- CI pipelines run the same container image used locally; there is no "it works on my machine"
- If a test requires a database, cache, or external service, define it as a service in `docker-compose.yml` and have the test container depend on it
- Never rely on a locally installed runtime, framework, or tool version — the container defines the environment

## Test Structure

- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA); separate each phase with a blank line
- One assertion focus per test — a test can have multiple `expect`/`assert` calls only if they all verify the same behavior
- No conditionals or loops inside test bodies — write separate test cases instead

## Naming

- Test names must read as a sentence: `test_returns_empty_list_when_no_results`, not `test_function_1`
- Group related tests in a class or `describe` block named after the unit under test

## TDD Workflow

- Write the failing test first, commit it, then implement
- Run the full suite in the container after every implementation step
- Red → Green → Refactor; do not skip the refactor step

## Mocking Discipline

- Mock at the boundary only: HTTP clients, databases, filesystems, queues
- Never mock code you own unless you are testing a seam deliberately
- Prefer a real in-container service (e.g., a test Postgres container) over a mock for persistence layers

## Coverage

- 80% line coverage minimum across the project
- 100% coverage on critical paths: authentication, authorization, payments, data mutations
- A failing coverage threshold blocks the container test run

## Test Isolation

- Each test sets up and tears down its own state — no shared mutable state between tests
- Database tests run in a transaction that is rolled back after each test, or use a dedicated test schema

## Flaky Tests

- A flaky test is a bug — treat it as one
- Mark it, file an issue, and fix or delete it; do not leave it retrying silently
